"""
MKT Context -- Luke 22
Output: data/commentary/mkt-context/luke.json

Luke 22 = The Passion Narrative: Passover preparation, Last Supper institution,
  Gethsemane prayer, arrest, Peter's denial, and the Sanhedrin hearing.

Key context decisions:
- Passover timing follows the 14 Nisan preparation-day / 15 Nisan meal framework
- "New covenant in my blood" reads Jer 31:31-34 as the deliberate OT background
- Gethsemane angel (v43) and sweat/blood (v44) noted as textually disputed
- Sanhedrin hearing at daybreak = informal examination before formal Pilate referral
- Luke's passion is notably distinct from Mark: no formal Sanhedrin condemnation,
  different saying order at Last Supper, unique Herod episode (follows in ch23)
"""
import json, pathlib
ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists(): return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    # INTENT: merge new_data into existing without overwriting any present entry
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing: existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]: existing[ch][v] = html

NEW = {
'22': {
'1': '<p>The Festival of Unleavened Bread (Hebrew: Hag ha-Matzot) was a seven-day pilgrimage feast (Exod 12:15-20; Lev 23:6-8; Deut 16:3-4) beginning on 15 Nisan; Passover (Pesach) was technically the 14 Nisan evening meal that inaugurated it. Luke\'s identification of the two -- "the Festival of Unleavened Bread, called the Passover" -- reflects the popular conflation of both festivals into a single extended celebration, as also in Josephus (Ant. 14.21; War 2.10). For pilgrims streaming into Jerusalem, "Passover" encompassed the whole week. The approach of this festival frames the passion narrative: the Passover was the year\'s defining act of redemption-memory, when Israel recalled the Exodus deliverance. Jesus\'s death will fall within this redemptive frame.</p>',
'2': '<p>The chief priests and teachers of the law were seeking a way to eliminate Jesus -- but "they were afraid of the people." This fear was structurally rational: Passover Jerusalem swelled with pilgrims from across the diaspora (Josephus War 6.425 gives a figure of 2,700,000 pilgrims, though modern estimates run 100,000-300,000). Any public action against a popular teacher during the festival risked sparking a crowd response that could destabilize Roman-Jewish arrangements and provoke Roman military intervention. The Sanhedrin\'s fear reflects the patron-client dynamic: their authority depended on Roman tolerance, and Roman tolerance depended on provincial order.</p>',
'4': '<p>Judas approached "the chief priests and the officers of the temple guard" (tois arch&#275;reusin kai tois stratēgois = the chief priests and the commanders/captains). The stratēgoi tou hierou (temple guard captains) were the Levitical police force responsible for maintaining order in the temple courts. Their inclusion alongside the chief priests identifies the meeting as involving both the priestly hierarchy and the enforcement arm of the Sanhedrin. Josephus (War 2.285-294) documents the significant power of this force; the temple captain (stratēgos) was second only to the high priest in the Jewish administration. Judas goes not to Rome but to the Jewish power structure.</p>',
'5': '<p>They "were delighted" (echarēsan = rejoiced) and agreed to give him money (argyrion = silver pieces). The precise amount is not given by Luke (Matthew 26:15 specifies thirty pieces of silver = the price of a slave in Exod 21:32; cf. Zech 11:12-13). The delight reflects the resolution of a practical problem: how to arrest Jesus away from crowds. The agreement created a contract -- an informal legal arrangement. In the patronage economy, such agreements involved obligations on both sides: Judas would deliver the prisoner; the authorities would pay. The money transforms the betrayal from an act of disillusionment into a commercial transaction.</p>',
'6': '<p>Judas "watched for an opportunity to hand Jesus over to them when no crowd was present" -- the Greek eukairan (a good/suitable moment, literally "good time") points to the problem the authorities faced. Timing the arrest to avoid a public reaction was strategically critical. The Gethsemane arrest (vv.47-53) occurs at night, outside the city, precisely in such an opportune moment. Ancient arrest procedure relied on surprise and isolation from potential defenders: the night garden arrest maximizes both conditions. Judas\'s role is specifically to provide the inside intelligence needed to locate Jesus at a vulnerable moment.</p>',
'7': '<p>The day the Passover lamb "had to be sacrificed" (edei thyesthai) -- on 14 Nisan, thousands of lambs were slaughtered in the temple courts in the afternoon hours before sunset. The Mishnah (m. Pesahim 5:1-10) gives detailed regulations: the slaughter began at 2:30 PM and if the 14th fell on a Sabbath, special provisions applied. The temple courts ran with blood; priests formed chains to pass the blood bowls to the altar. Each family or group needed a lamb between 1 and 12 months old, unblemished (Exod 12:5). The sheer scale of the operation -- tens of thousands of lambs -- made this the most dramatic liturgical event of the Jewish calendar.</p>',
'8': '<p>Jesus sends Peter and John specifically to make Passover preparations. The Passover preparation (hetoimasate = prepare, make ready) involved: procuring and sacrificing the lamb, acquiring unleavened bread (matzah), bitter herbs (maror), and the sauce (charoset), and preparing the venue. Peter and John are sent on this task -- the two who will also be the inner circle at Gethsemane (though Luke does not distinguish them there as Mark does). The selection of Peter and John as the advance team reflects their status as the core disciples; the mission is entrusted to those who can be trusted with the secret location.</p>',
'9': '<p>"Where do you want us to prepare it?" -- the question reveals that no preparation site had been pre-arranged publicly. The secrecy of the preparation instructions (vv.10-12) protected Jesus\'s ability to have an uninterrupted Passover meal before the arrest. If Judas knew the location of the meal in advance, the arrest could occur during the supper rather than afterward in Gethsemane. The "man carrying a jar of water" (vv.10-12) is probably a pre-arranged signal with a sympathizer whose identity Jesus keeps from the disciples to prevent Judas from learning the location.</p>',
'10': '<p>A man carrying a jar of water (keramion hydatos = a clay jug of water) was an unusual sight: women normally carried water jars; men carried wineskins. The signal is therefore easily recognizable without being a message that could be intercepted or misunderstood. This kind of pre-arranged sign (a person carrying an unusual object) was a standard covert-meeting protocol. The instruction to "follow him to the house he enters" suggests the sympathizer knows the plan but is not introduced to the disciples by name -- minimizing the information Judas could extract from them.</p>',
'11': '<p>"The Teacher asks: Where is the guest room (katalyma) where I may eat the Passover with my disciples?" -- katalyma (the same word used for "inn" in 2:7 at the birth) is a guest room in a private house, not a commercial establishment. The address to "the owner of the house" (t&#333; oikodespot&#275; t&#275;s oikias = the householder) identifies this as a private arrangement with a Jerusalem family who was a follower or sympathizer. Jerusalem households regularly prepared such rooms for Passover pilgrims, and a room already furnished (v.12) suggests it was kept ready for anticipated use by Jesus and his group.</p>',
'12': '<p>"A large room upstairs, all furnished" (anag&#275;on mega estrōmenon) -- the upper room (anag&#275;on or hyperōon: the upper story of a Mediterranean house, where guests were hosted and important meals held) was the prestige venue for a meal. Jewish houses in Jerusalem often had upper-story rooms accessible by interior or exterior stairs. The "furnished" (estrōmenon = spread/equipped, i.e., couches and table already arranged) detail indicates the host had made ready in advance. First-century Jewish Passover practice involved reclining at a triclinium-style table, representing the posture of free persons, not slaves -- a deliberate inversion of the Egyptian slavery context.</p>',
'13': '<p>The disciples find "things just as Jesus had told them" (kath&#333;s eirēken autois) -- the fulfillment of the sign functions as a demonstration of Jesus\'s foreknowledge, which Luke uses consistently in the passion narrative (the sign, the prediction of Peter\'s denial, the passion predictions). The Passover preparation is completed by Peter and John: the lamb slaughtered in the temple, the room secured, the meal ready. Luke places the completion matter-of-factly, in contrast to Mark\'s more extended version. The smooth fulfillment of the sign prepares the reader for the larger pattern: what is happening to Jesus occurs according to divine planning, not random historical forces.</p>',
'14': '<p>"When the hour came" (h&#275; hora = the hour -- a Lukan and Johannine term for the appointed time of the passion, cf. 22:53; John 12:23; 13:1; 17:1) -- Jesus and the apostles (apostoloi -- Luke uses this title more consistently than the Synoptic parallels; cf. 6:13 where Luke alone records Jesus naming them "apostles") reclined at table. Reclining (anaklitheis = laying back, leaning on one\'s elbow) was the posture of the Passover meal, required by the Mishnah (m. Pesahim 10:1: "even the poorest man in Israel must not eat [on the Passover night] unless he reclines") as a sign of freedom. The posture embodied the meaning: they were celebrating liberation from slavery.</p>',
'15': '<p>"I have eagerly desired to eat this Passover with you before I suffer" -- epithumia epethumēsa = I have desired with desire (a Hebraism: the cognate accusative intensifies the verb, like infinitive absolute in Hebrew). Jesus\'s intense desire for this meal is unique to Luke and frames it as deeply personal: not merely a ritual obligation but the appointed culmination of his mission. The phrase "before I suffer" (pro tou me pathein = before my suffering) uses pathos language -- the early Christian technical term for Jesus\'s passion. The meal is situated as the last shared moment before the cross: the Passover of liberation precedes the Passover lamb\'s sacrifice.</p>',
'16': '<p>"I will not eat it again until it finds fulfillment in the kingdom of God" -- the eschatological fulfillment (pl&#275;rōth&#275; en t&#275; basileia tou theou = is fulfilled in the kingdom of God) points to the Messianic banquet tradition. Isaiah 25:6-8 describes "a feast of rich food for all peoples" on the mountain of the Lord when death is swallowed up forever. The Mishnah (m. Berakhot 6-7) and Talmud (b. Pesahim 119b) preserve traditions about a future eschatological meal. Jewish apocalyptic literature (1 Enoch 62:14; 2 Bar. 29:4) depicts the righteous eating with the Messiah. The Passover Jesus celebrates will find its completion in that final feast.</p>',
'17': '<p>Luke\'s Supper begins with a cup (vv.17-18) before the bread (v.19) -- a sequence unique to Luke, possibly reflecting a different version of the eucharistic tradition or describing an early Passover cup (the Haggadah includes four cups of wine at Passover: Kiddush, Haggadah, Blessing, and Hallel). The first-century Passover Seder involved up to four cups of wine, each with a specific liturgical function. "He gave thanks" (eucharist&#275;sas = having given thanks -- the root of "Eucharist") reflects the Jewish b&#275;rakhah (blessing/thanksgiving) over the cup: "Blessed are you, LORD our God, King of the universe, who creates the fruit of the vine."</p>',
'18': '<p>"I will not drink again from the fruit of the vine until the kingdom of God comes" -- the abstention vow parallels the Nazirite vow structure (Num 6:3-4; cf. Acts 21:26) and the Jewish practice of making vows of abstention as acts of anticipatory dedication. The vow frames the meal as the last before the Kingdom\'s arrival. The "fruit of the vine" (genn&#275;matos t&#275;s ampelou = product of the vine) is the liturgical phrase from the Kiddush blessing over Passover wine. Jesus\'s vow connects the present Passover to the eschatological fulfillment: the cup he will not drink until then corresponds to the cup of the Kingdom he described in v.16.</p>',
'19': '<p>"He took bread, gave thanks and broke it, and gave it to them, saying: This is my body given for you; do this in remembrance of me" -- the institution of the Lord\'s Supper in Luke follows the form preserved by Paul in 1 Cor 11:23-25 more closely than it follows Mark 14:22-24. "Given for you" (to hyper hym&#333;n didomenon = the one being given on your behalf) uses the preposition hyper (on behalf of, for the sake of) which in Greek sacrificial and military language denoted representative action: one person acting in the place or stead of others. The "remembrance" (anamn&#275;sin = re-presentation, making present again) is drawn from the Passover command (Exod 12:14: "This is a day you are to commemorate") -- the Passover meal itself was a ritual anamnesis of the Exodus.</p>',
'20': '<p>"In the same way, after the supper he took the cup, saying: This cup is the new covenant in my blood, which is poured out for you" -- the explicit citation of the "new covenant" (kain&#275; diathēk&#275;) invokes Jer 31:31-34 as the deliberate OT background: "The days are coming, declares the LORD, when I will make a new covenant with the people of Israel and with the people of Judah... I will forgive their wickedness and will remember their sins no more." Jesus declares his blood to be the founding act of the new covenant Jeremiah promised. "Poured out for you" (ekchynnomenon hyper hym&#333;n) draws on the Servant\'s self-offering in Isa 53:12: "he poured out his life unto death."</p>',
'21': '<p>"But the hand of him who is going to betray me is with mine on the table" -- the placement of the betrayal announcement after the institution of the Supper (as opposed to Mark\'s pre-institution placement) is distinctive to Luke. In the Lukan sequence, Judas has participated in the Eucharist before the betrayal is announced, which deepens the horror: the betrayal is the violation of shared table, the most intimate social bond. The shared table (the hand on the table together) was in the ancient Mediterranean world the supreme expression of covenant loyalty and trust. To betray a table-companion was the deepest form of treachery (cf. Ps 41:9: "Even my close friend, someone I trusted, one who shared my bread, has turned against me").</p>',
'22': '<p>"The Son of Man will go as it has been decreed (kata to h&#333;rismenos = according to what has been determined/appointed)" -- h&#333;riz&#333; (to appoint, determine, mark off) is used in Acts 2:23 ("handed over to you by God\'s deliberate plan and foreknowledge") and 17:31 to describe divine determination of events. The passive "decreed" implies divine agency: what is happening to Jesus is not an accident of history but the outworking of divine purpose. Yet the same verse pronounces "woe" on the betrayer: divine necessity and human responsibility coexist. The double statement holds together what later theology will work to distinguish -- God\'s sovereignty and human culpability do not cancel each other.</p>',
'23': '<p>The disciples begin questioning among themselves (syz&#275;tein = to investigate together, to debate) which of them might do this. The question reveals the moral seriousness of the community: none of them assumes someone else is obviously capable of betrayal; none immediately suspects Judas. The setting -- the Passover table -- makes the question more urgent. Passover night was supposed to be a time of solidarity, the meal of liberation; the revelation that one of the twelve is a traitor disrupts the covenant fellowship of the meal. The disciples\' genuine perplexity about who it could be is also a Lukan device: Judas is not distinguishable from the others by visible wickedness.</p>',
'24': '<p>The dispute about greatness (philoneikia = love of strife, contentiousness -- also the word used in Polybius for factional conflict) occurring at the Last Supper is shocking in its placement. Immediately after the institution of the Eucharist -- the self-giving act of Jesus -- the disciples argue about which of them is the greatest. The honor-shame culture of the first-century Mediterranean made status ranking a constant preoccupation: at any gathering, the question of precedence (who sits where, who is served first, who receives public recognition) was socially charged. The symposium setting -- a meal with discussion -- made this even more explicit, as the symposium traditionally involved a formal ranking of participants.</p>',
'25': '<p>"The kings of the Gentiles lord it over them; and those who exercise authority over them call themselves Benefactors (Euergetes)" -- Euergetes (Benefactor) was an official royal title in the Hellenistic world. Ptolemy III was called Euergetes; Antiochus VII bore the title. The Seleucid and Ptolemaic courts institutionalized the "benefactor" language as a mechanism of royal self-legitimation: the king\'s generosity (giving gifts, building temples, hosting feasts) was publicly acknowledged through the title, creating a cycle of patronage and honor. Jesus identifies this system -- genuine benefaction exchanged for public honor and titles -- as the dominant Gentile model of power.</p>',
'26': '<p>"But you are not to be like that. Instead, the greatest among you should be like the youngest, and the one who rules like the one who serves" -- the inversion of the honor-shame hierarchy is radical within Mediterranean cultural logic. The youngest (neos) at a table occupied the lowest-status position: seated last, served last, silent in the presence of elders. The servant (diakonōn = one who serves at table) was not a status role but a functional one -- literally the person who moved between kitchen and table. Jesus places both of these low-status roles as the model for leadership in his community. This is not merely rhetorical humility but a structural redefinition of authority.</p>',
'27': '<p>"For who is greater, the one who is at the table or the one who serves? Is it not the one at the table? But I am among you as one who serves" -- the rhetorical question uses the conventional answer to undermine the convention. Yes, by social logic, the reclined guest at the feast is greater than the table-servant. Jesus then reverses the logic: "I am among you as the diakonōn." At the Last Supper, the host of the meal -- the teacher, the one with greatest claim to honor -- is serving his disciples. John 13:4-5 makes this concrete with the foot-washing. The master who serves is the new paradigm for the community\'s leadership structure.</p>',
'28': '<p>"You are those who have stood by me (diamen&#275;kotes met\' emou) in my trials (peirasmos)" -- peirasmos here means trials/testings, not temptation: the hardships Jesus has faced in his ministry (rejection, opposition, lack of resources, physical danger). The disciples are honored for their perseverance through these: the word diamenō (to remain through, continue with) emphasizes loyal endurance over time. Luke\'s travel narrative has highlighted the disciples\' repeated failures to understand, yet here Jesus credits them with faithful presence. The honor Jesus confers is based not on rank or ability but on loyalty through adversity.</p>',
'29': '<p>"I confer on you a kingdom, just as my Father conferred one on me" -- the verb diatithemai (to confer, dispose, covenant) is the word used for making a covenant or will. The "conferring of a kingdom" is a formal royal grant: the Father has granted Jesus the Kingdom; Jesus in turn grants it to the apostles. This is the language of the Davidic covenant (2 Sam 7:12-16; Ps 89:3-4) applied in an elevated register: the Son of David receives the eternal kingdom and shares it with his faithful. The conferral at the Last Supper, on the eve of the passion, is deliberately paradoxical -- the king grants thrones while going to his own execution.</p>',
'30': '<p>"So that you may eat and drink at my table in my kingdom and sit on thrones, judging the twelve tribes of Israel" -- the Messianic banquet promise (eating at Jesus\'s table in the Kingdom) echoes Isa 25:6-8. The "twelve thrones" saying appears in Matt 19:28 in a different context; Luke places it here in the upper room as part of the apostles\' installation. The "judging of the twelve tribes" (krinein tas d&#333;deka phylas tou Isr&#275;&#275;l) uses the OT sense of krinein as governing/ruling, not merely pronouncing sentence (cf. Judg 2:16-19 where judges "saved" and "governed" Israel). The restoration of the twelve tribes is a standard Jewish eschatological expectation (Ezek 37:19-24; Pss. Sol. 17:28-32).</p>',
'31': '<p>"Simon, Simon, Satan has asked (ex&#275;t&#275;sato = requested, demanded) to sift all of you as wheat" -- the doubled name ("Simon, Simon") is a form of urgent personal address unique in Luke (cf. 10:41: "Martha, Martha"; Acts 9:4: "Saul, Saul"). The imagery of sifting wheat was familiar from agricultural life: grain was thrown into a sieve and shaken to separate kernels from chaff. Satan has "requested" (ex&#275;t&#275;sato = asked permission from, demanded) to put the disciples through this trial. The language echoes Job 1-2, where Satan presents himself before God and requests permission to test Job: cosmic adversarial testing operates within divine permission. The disciples face a Job-like ordeal.</p>',
'32': '<p>"But I have prayed for you (peri sou = concerning you, singular -- addressed to Simon alone, not the group) that your faith may not fail. And when you have turned back, strengthen your brothers" -- the singular "you" separates Peter from the group: Jesus prays specifically for Peter\'s faith (not that he won\'t deny, but that his faith won\'t ultimately fail). "When you have turned back" (epistrephas = having turned around/repented) presupposes the denial: the turning back is not a conditional but a certainty. "Strengthen your brothers" (st&#275;rison tous adelphous sou = make firm your brothers) gives Peter a post-denial mission: the very failure becomes the qualification for pastoral responsibility. Peter\'s brokenness and restoration are preparatory, not disqualifying.</p>',
'33': '<p>"Lord, I am ready to go with you to prison and to death" -- Peter\'s protestation reflects the honor code: a man who claimed loyalty to a patron was expected to demonstrate it under test. The protestation "to prison and to death" (eis phylak&#275;n kai eis thanaton = into prison and into death) follows the ascending scale of commitment. In the first-century context, arrest for association with a seditious teacher was a real risk. Peter\'s claim is genuine, not hypocritical: he believes he means it. The subsequent denial (vv.54-62) does not expose Peter as a coward but as a human being who discovers that courage cannot be guaranteed by resolve alone, only by the grace Jesus has already secured for him (v.32).</p>',
'34': '<p>"Before the rooster crows today, you will deny three times that you know me" -- the prediction is precise: today (before the current day ends), the rooster (al&#275;ktōr = rooster, the timekeeper of the night watches), three times (tris), and deny knowing Jesus (aparn&#275;s&#275; = disown, renounce -- stronger than "not know"). The four Roman night watches were named: evening, midnight, cock-crow, and morning. The "cock-crow" watch was approximately 3 AM. Peter\'s denial (vv.56-60) occurs during the fourth watch (Luke\'s "about an hour later" suggesting dawn). The precision of the prediction is part of Luke\'s passion theology: everything occurring according to foreknown divine plan.</p>',
'35': '<p>"When I sent you without purse, bag or sandals, did you lack anything?" -- the reference is to the mission of the Seventy (10:4: "Do not take a purse or bag or sandals") and implicitly to the earlier Twelve mission (9:3: "Take nothing for the journey -- no staff, no bag, no bread, no money, no extra shirt"). The mission instructions had prohibited standard travel provisions; the disciples had traveled in radical dependence on hospitality. Their answer "Nothing" (ouden = nothing at all) confirms that the dependence-model worked: they were provided for throughout. This establishes the contrast with the coming changed conditions (v.36).</p>',
'36': '<p>"But now if you have a purse, take it, and also a bag; and if you don\'t have a sword, sell your cloak and buy one" -- the changed instructions signal the changed conditions of the post-passion era. The disciples will no longer travel in the protected space of Jesus\'s immediate presence, where his authority provided social cover. The "sword" (machairan = short sword, also the word for a large knife) instruction has been variously interpreted: (1) literal self-defense preparation; (2) symbolic readiness for conflict; (3) deliberate fulfillment of Isa 53:12 (v.37: "he was numbered with the transgressors"). The disciples\' response of "here are two swords" and Jesus\'s "that is enough" suggests the literal reading misses the point.</p>',
'37': '<p>"It is written: And he was numbered with the transgressors (meta anom&#333;n elogisth&#275;)" -- a direct quotation from Isa 53:12 (LXX: kai en tois anomois elogisth&#275;). This is the key to interpreting the sword instruction: Jesus is not organizing a military defense but explaining that what is about to happen fulfills the Servant\'s fate. The Servant of Isaiah 53 is "numbered with transgressors" -- classified alongside criminals. Jesus\'s arrest with swords (as if he were a revolutionary, v.52) will make this literal: he will be treated as an outlaw. "What is written about me is reaching its fulfillment (telos echei = is coming to its end/completion)" -- the passion is the goal toward which the Servant songs have been pointing.</p>',
'38': '<p>The disciples\' "See, Lord, here are two swords" (idou machairai h&#333;de dyo = behold, two swords here) and Jesus\'s "That is enough!" (hikanos estin = it is sufficient) -- the disciples have taken the sword instruction literally. Jesus\'s response "That is enough!" (which has been interpreted variously: enough swords, enough of this conversation, enough of literal misunderstanding) seems to cut off a direction of thought rather than endorse it. Two swords are obviously inadequate for military resistance; the response appears to end the discussion. The disciples\' persistent literal-mindedness in the face of Jesus\'s symbolic language is a consistent Lukan theme (cf. the disciples arguing about greatness in v.24).</p>',
'39': '<p>"Jesus went out as usual to the Mount of Olives" (kata to ethos = according to his custom) -- the Mount of Olives became the disciples\' nightly camp during the Passover week, as Luke 21:37 records: "Each evening he went out to spend the night on the hill called the Mount of Olives." The Kidron Valley separated Jerusalem from the Mount of Olives; pilgrims who could not find lodging within the city walls camped on the surrounding hillsides. Gethsemane (Hebrew: gat sh&#277;mānīm = olive oil press) was a garden in the valley near the Kidron. The routine -- Jesus consistently going to the same place -- makes Judas\'s betrayal via a specific location easier: Judas knows where to find Jesus at night.</p>',
'40': '<p>"On reaching the place (ton topon -- the specific place; Luke\'s definite article implies the disciples know this location), he said to them: Pray that you will not fall into temptation (peirasmon = trial, testing, temptation)" -- the instruction bookends the Gethsemane section (repeated at v.46): the disciples are told to pray at both the beginning and end of Jesus\'s prayer. Peirasmos here connects to Satan\'s requested sifting (v.31): the disciples face the same trial Jesus faces. The prayer "that you will not fall into" (hina m&#275; eiselth&#275;te eis = that you may not enter into) is the prayer of the Lord\'s Prayer (11:4: "Lead us not into temptation"). The disciples are not invited to pray that the trial won\'t come, but that they won\'t yield to it.</p>',
'41': '<p>"He withdrew about a stone\'s throw beyond them, knelt down and prayed" -- the "stone\'s throw" (lithou bol&#275;n = a stone\'s throw distance, approximately 30-40 meters) gives both physical separation and maintained visible connection. The posture is notable: Jesus "knelt down" (theis ta gonata = setting the knees) rather than the more common standing posture for prayer. Kneeling signified extreme need or crisis (cf. Acts 7:60; 9:40; 20:36; 21:5). Mark 14:35 has Jesus "falling to the ground"; Matthew 26:39 has him "falling on his face" -- the intensifying versions suggest the anguish of the prayer. Luke\'s "knelt" is still a posture of crisis, not the casual posture of routine prayer.</p>',
'42': '<p>"Father, if you are willing, take this cup from me; yet not my will, but yours be done" -- the cup (to pot&#275;rion) is the OT image of God\'s judgment or wrath that must be drunk (Ps 75:8; Isa 51:17-22; Jer 25:15-16; Ezek 23:31-33; Hab 2:16). The cup Jesus asks to have removed is not simply the physical suffering of crucifixion but the cup of divine wrath that Isaiah 51:17 describes as making Jerusalem "stagger" -- the experience of bearing the full weight of God\'s judgment. The conditional "if you are willing" (ei boulei = if you are willing, if it is your will) frames the request as genuinely petitionary without coercion. The "yet not my will, but yours" (all\' m&#275; to thelēma mou alla to son ginetō) is the submission of the second Adam where the first Adam disobeyed.</p>',
'43': '<p>"An angel from heaven appeared to him and strengthened him" (enischyōn auton = strengthening him, imparting strength to him) -- this verse (along with v.44) is absent from some important manuscripts (P75, Vaticanus, Alexandrinus) but present in others (Sinaiticus, many early versions). The textual question is genuine. If original: the angel\'s strengthening reflects the OT pattern of divine provision to human ministers in extremity (1 Kgs 19:5-7: an angel strengthening Elijah; Dan 10:18: the "one like a man" strengthening Daniel). The angel does not remove the cup but enables Jesus to continue drinking it. If a later addition: it may have been inserted to protect the full humanity of Jesus against docetic tendencies, or to avoid the apparent weakness of angelic aid.</p>',
'44': '<p>"And being in anguish (en ag&#333;nia = in agony/anguish), he prayed more earnestly, and his sweat was like drops of blood falling to the ground" -- ag&#333;nia is the word for the intense effort of an athletic contest (ag&#333;n) or battle: the all-out expenditure of one\'s strength. The sweat "like drops of blood" (h&#333;sei thromboi haimatos = as it were clots of blood) has been variously interpreted: (1) actual bloody sweat (hematidrosis, a rare medical condition under extreme psychological stress, noted by Aristotle and reported by Galen); (2) simile only ("like clots," not actual blood); (3) the sweat falling "to the ground" like large drops, compared to blood clots in density. The textual uncertainty of v.43-44 applies here too. If original to Luke, the emphasis is on the genuine human extremity of Jesus\'s prayer.</p>',
'45': '<p>"When he rose from prayer and went back to the disciples, he found them asleep, exhausted from sorrow (apo t&#275;s lyp&#275;s = from the grief/sorrow)" -- Luke\'s unique explanation for the disciples\' sleep. Mark 14:37-38 attributes their sleep to simple failure ("the spirit is willing but the body is weak"); Luke attributes it to grief (lyp&#275; = pain, grief, sorrow). The disciples are not callously indifferent but emotionally overwhelmed: they have heard the passion predictions; the Last Supper has made the coming events vivid; the Gethsemane atmosphere communicates crisis. Luke\'s characterization is more sympathetic: the disciples sleep from emotional exhaustion, not mere physical tiredness. Even so, the failure to pray leaves them unprepared for the trial that follows.</p>',
'46': '<p>"Why are you sleeping? Get up and pray so that you will not fall into temptation" -- the rebuke is gentler in Luke than in Mark, where Jesus expresses explicit disappointment. The framing of the rebuke as a return to the instruction of v.40 (the same prayer command) creates a chiasm around the Gethsemane prayer: the disciples should be praying what Jesus has been praying, but they have slept through the model. The coming trial (Peter\'s denial, the scattering) will demonstrate the cost of that failure to pray. Luke\'s theology here: prayer (specifically, praying "not to enter into temptation") is the preparation for sustaining faith under crisis. The disciples who didn\'t pray will fail the test; Jesus who did will face it in submission.</p>',
'47': '<p>Judas leading the crowd: he was one of the Twelve (heis t&#333;n d&#333;deka -- the designation of infamy, repeated each time Judas is mentioned: 6:16; 22:3, 47) who was leading the group. The crowd (ochlos = the general term for a mob, not a technical arrest party) sent by the chief priests and Sanhedrin included temple guards and, according to John 18:3, a Roman cohort (speira = a detachment of soldiers, 100-600 men). Luke\'s "crowd" may reflect a mixed force. The pre-arranged signal (a kiss) presupposes darkness: the garden at night, lit by torches (John 18:3), required a prearranged identification to ensure arresting the right person.</p>',
'48': '<p>"Judas, are you betraying the Son of Man with a kiss?" -- the question (only in Luke) addresses Judas by name, publicly, and names the action as betrayal (paradids&#333;s = are you handing over / betraying). The kiss (philein = to kiss) was a standard greeting between teacher and disciple (the form kataphilein = to kiss warmly, as in the prodigal son 15:20) and a sign of affiliation and honor. Using it as a betrayal signal is the perversion of covenant greeting: the act of loyalty becomes the instrument of betrayal. The "Son of Man" title in this context invokes Dan 7:13 -- the one destined for exaltation being handed over -- framing the arrest as paradox: the cosmic figure being betrayed by a handshake.</p>',
'49': '<p>"When Jesus\' followers saw what was going to happen, they said: Lord, should we strike with our swords?" -- the disciples\' question "shall we strike?" (ei pataxomen en machair&#275; = shall we strike with a sword) echoes the sword-preparation of vv.36-38. Having interpreted the sword instruction literally, they now apply it literally. The irony: they had the two swords; they ask permission; Jesus does not give it; one strikes anyway (v.50). The question "shall we strike?" addressed to "Lord" frames their action as seeking divine authorization for what they had already decided to do. The conditional phrasing doesn\'t wait for the answer.</p>',
'50': '<p>"And one of them struck the servant of the high priest, cutting off his right ear" -- only John 18:10 names the attacker (Peter) and the servant (Malchus). Luke\'s "one of them" (heis tis ex aut&#333;n) anonymizes the act, which may reflect the protection of Peter at the time of writing (the tradition could endanger him). The servant of the high priest (tou arch&#275;re&#333;s ton doulon) was a member of the high priest\'s household: his presence indicates the official character of the arrest. Cutting off the ear (apeilen auton to ous to dexion = cut off from him the ear, the right one) would have permanently disqualified the servant from temple service under Lev 21:17-21 (which prohibited priestly service for those with physical defects). Luke alone records the healing (v.51).</p>',
'51': '<p>"But Jesus answered: No more of this! (Eate h&#275;os toutou = Allow until this / let this go no further) And he touched the man\'s ear and healed him" -- Luke is the only Gospel to record the healing of the ear. The act is characteristically Lukan: even in his arrest, Jesus heals. The healing demonstrates continued mission and mercy while demonstrating that Jesus is not arrested against his will but submits. The legal implication may also be present: healing the ear removes the evidence of violence that could be used to prosecute the disciples as well as demonstrating Jesus\'s authority over the situation even as he is being taken. The command "No more of this" shuts down the disciples\' instinct for armed resistance.</p>',
'52': '<p>Jesus addresses "the chief priests, the officers of the temple guard, and the elders" -- all three components of the Sanhedrin\'s authority structure are present at the arrest. Their personal appearance at a nighttime arrest in a garden (rather than delegating the arrest to temple police) indicates the importance they placed on capturing Jesus. The question "Am I leading a rebellion?" (h&#333;s epi l&#275;st&#275;n = as against a bandit/revolutionary) -- l&#275;st&#275;s is the word Josephus uses for the Zealot-style freedom fighters and bandits of first-century Judea (War 2.253-254). Jesus points out the contradiction: they are treating him as if he were an armed insurrectionist when he has been publicly teaching in the temple daily.</p>',
'53': '<p>"Every day I was with you in the temple courts, and you did not lay a hand on me. But this is your hour -- when darkness reigns" (h&#275; ex&#275; hymōn kai h&#275; exousia tou skotous = your hour and the authority of darkness) -- the theological interpretation of the arrest: it occurs not because of Jewish or Roman power but because of a specific permitted moment of darkness\'s authority. Darkness (skotos) in Luke-Acts carries the connotation of satanic power (cf. v.3: "Satan entered Judas"; v.31: Satan asking to sift the disciples; Acts 26:18: "turn them from darkness to light... from the power of Satan to God"). The "hour of darkness" echoes John 12:23 ("the hour has come") and John 3:19 ("people loved darkness instead of light"). The cross is paradoxically the moment of darkness\'s maximum exercise of power and its definitive defeat.</p>',
'54': '<p>"Then seizing him, they led him away and took him into the house of the high priest. Peter followed at a distance" -- the high priest\'s house (aul&#275; = courtyard; the broader compound, not merely a room) was probably in the Upper City of Jerusalem, the aristocratic quarter where the high priestly families lived. Josephus describes this area (War 2.426-427). The house would have had an enclosed courtyard. "Peter followed at a distance" (akolouth&#275;n de makrothen = following from afar) is the technically correct description of a sympathizer who cannot yet break with Jesus but will not identify himself as a disciple. The distance -- social as well as physical -- sets up the denial narrative.</p>',
'55': '<p>"And when some there had kindled a fire in the middle of the courtyard and had sat down together, Peter sat down with them" -- the courtyard fire (pyria = fire lit for warmth) was necessary in early spring Jerusalem: the nights in late Nisan can be cold (the temperature in Jerusalem drops to ~10°C/50°F at night). Sitting around a fire was a social act: it created a circle of visibility and community. Peter sits down with the servants and officers -- those who had just arrested Jesus. The firelight that reveals Peter to the servant girl (v.56) is thus the same fire that warms him: the social comfort of the fire exposes him. The scene is carefully constructed by Luke as a space of judgment and visibility.</p>',
'56': '<p>The servant girl (paidisk&#275; = young female slave) "saw him seated there in the firelight. She looked closely at him" (atenisasa aut&#333; = staring intently at him, the same word used for Stephen\'s vision in Acts 7:55) "and said: This man was with him." The recognition is visual and social: Peter\'s face, known to those in the household of a significant Jerusalem family (the high priest\'s network would have encountered Jesus\'s group repeatedly), is visible in the firelight. The servant girl\'s accusation is casual and direct -- she doesn\'t accuse him to authority but makes the observation to those around the fire. The social pressure is the accusation itself: those nearby now look at Peter.</p>',
'57': '<p>"But he denied it. Woman, I don\'t know him (ouk oida auton = I do not know him)" -- the denial (hērnēsato = he denied, disowned) uses the same root as Peter\'s protestation (v.33: "I am ready..."). The irony is deliberate. "Woman" (gynai = a respectful but distancing form of address, the same word Jesus uses for his mother at Cana: John 2:4) creates formal distance from the servant girl and from the accusation. "I don\'t know him" -- the verb oida (to know by acquaintance, experiential knowledge) is the strongest possible disavowal: not "I\'m not associated with him" but "this person is unknown to me." The first denial is private, to those at the fire.</p>',
'58': '<p>"A little later (meta brachy) someone else saw him and said: You also are one of them. Man, I am not! (Anthr&#333;pe, ouk eimi = Man, I am not) Peter replied" -- the second denier is "someone else" (heteros tis = a different person), masculine (the servant girl who saw him was a paidisk&#275;; this accuser is different). The accusation is now public and direct: "You also are one of them" (kai sy ex aut&#333;n ei = you also are from them). Peter\'s denial "Man, I am not!" uses the vocative anthr&#333;pe (Man! = a somewhat dismissive address to a social equal or inferior) and the emphatic ouk eimi. The escalation across the three denials is subtle but present in Luke: the denials become more emphatic.</p>',
'59': '<p>"About an hour later (diastasis&#275;s h&#333;sei h&#333;ras mias = an interval of about one hour having elapsed) another asserted: Certainly (ep\' al&#275;theias = in truth, truly) this fellow was with him, for he is a Galilean" -- the hour\'s gap between the second and third accusation makes Peter\'s continued presence at the fire remarkable: he stays despite the growing social danger. The evidence cited is now geographical: the Galilean accent (Matt 26:73 explicitly mentions the accent; Luke describes only the assertion of Galilean origin). Galilean speech had identifiable characteristics noted by rabbinic sources (m. Eruvin 53b: Galileans had difficulty distinguishing between gutturals). The geographical identification connects him to Jesus of Nazareth.</p>',
'60': '<p>"Peter replied: Man, I don\'t know what you\'re talking about!" (Anthr&#333;pe, ouk oida ho legeis = Man, I do not know what you say) -- the third denial escalates to complete dissociation: not just "I don\'t know him" but "I don\'t even understand what you\'re talking about." The dramatic moment: "Just as he was speaking (eti lalountos autou = while he was still speaking), the rooster crowed." The simultaneous occurrence of the denial and the crow is the clock that Jesus had predicted (v.34: "before the rooster crows today"). The prediction\'s exact fulfillment is the mechanism of Peter\'s remembering (v.61).</p>',
'61': '<p>"The Lord turned and looked straight at Peter. Then Peter remembered the word the Lord had spoken to him: Before the rooster crows today, you will deny me three times" -- Luke uniquely records "the Lord turned and looked" (straphe&#237;s ho kyrios eneblepsen t&#333; Petr&#333; = having turned, the Lord looked into Peter). The Lord\'s look -- from within the high priest\'s house to the courtyard -- is a moment of devastating relational presence. The use of "the Lord" (ho kyrios) rather than "Jesus" gives the look its theological weight: it is not merely a human glance but the gaze of the one Peter has just denied three times knowing. The look does not condemn but recalls: Peter "remembered the word" (emn&#275;sth&#275; tou r&#275;matos = was reminded of the word).</p>',
'62': '<p>"And he went outside and wept bitterly" (eklaisen pikr&#333;s = wept bitterly, intensely) -- the outside (ex&#333;) marks Peter\'s departure from both the physical space and the social situation: the courtyard, the fire, the pretense. Bitter weeping (pikr&#333;s = bitterly, sharply -- the same word in the LXX for the lamentation of the bereaved: Isa 22:4) is the expression of genuine grief, not merely embarrassment. This is repentance beginning -- not yet the full restoration (which occurs in John 21:15-19), but the crack in the self-sufficiency that Jesus\'s prayer (v.32: "that your faith may not fail") had prepared for. The bitterness of the weeping corresponds to the depth of the love that was denied.</p>',
'63': '<p>"The men who were guarding Jesus began mocking and beating him" -- the guards (hoi andres hoi synechontes = the men holding him, restraining him) are the temple police who have custody of Jesus overnight before the Sanhedrin hearing at daybreak. Their mockery and beating is a night of suffering that Luke narrates without the formal trial Mark and Matthew place before it. Luke\'s sequence has the informal custody, the mocking/beating, then the morning Sanhedrin hearing (v.66) -- a different arrangement from Mark 14:53-65 where the night council meeting and the mocking are placed together. Both accounts describe genuine physical abuse before any judicial proceeding.</p>',
'64': '<p>"They blindfolded him and demanded: Prophesy! Who hit you?" -- the blindfold (perikalypsantes = having covered around) and the demand to prophesy by identifying the striker is a game of mockery that inverts Jesus\'s identity: he is claimed to be a prophet, so they test him in a way designed to make him fail. The same challenge appears in similar form in other contexts where prisoners were taunted: Josephus (War 6.300-309) records a man named Jesus bar Ananias being beaten and asked to identify his accusers. The mockery is not random cruelty but pointed: they are mocking the specific claim that made Jesus dangerous -- his prophetic and messianic identity.</p>',
'65': '<p>"And they said many other insulting things to him" (hetero polla blasph&#275;mountes = many other things they were blaspheming against him) -- blasph&#275;mein (to blaspheme, defame, slander) applied to speech against human beings means abusive/insulting speech; it is the same word applied to speech against God. The irony Luke sees in the word: those who accuse Jesus of blasphemy (v.71) are themselves engaging in blasphemy against the one who is more than a man. The night of mockery is the human side of the dark hour Jesus identified in v.53: the "authority of darkness" expressing itself through human contempt for the Son of Man.</p>',
'66': '<p>"At daybreak (h&#275;meras genomenas = day having arrived, at dawn) the council of the elders of the people, both the chief priests and the teachers of the law, met together (synēchth&#275; to presbyterion = the council of elders gathered), and Jesus was led before their council (sanedrion)" -- the Sanhedrin (from the Greek synedrion = sitting together, council) was the supreme Jewish governing and judicial body. It was composed of the high priest, chief priests, elders (lay aristocrats), and scribes (legal experts). The meeting at daybreak is significant: Jewish law required that capital sentences be confirmed in daylight (m. Sanhedrin 4:1: "In capital cases, the verdict of acquittal may be reached on the same day, but the verdict of conviction not until the following day"). The daybreak meeting may represent the formal confirmation of a night decision.</p>',
'67': '<p>"If you are the Messiah, tell us" -- the question goes directly to the identity that Jesus has been performing (entry into Jerusalem, temple cleansing, authoritative teaching). Jesus\'s answer "If I tell you, you will not believe me" is not evasion but a diagnosis of the situation. The Sanhedrin\'s "if" (ei sy ei ho Christos = if you are the Christ) already signals skepticism: they are not genuinely inquiring but seeking a statement to use legally. Jesus\'s response points to the fundamental problem: the question is not about evidence but about the willingness to believe. They have already seen the evidence (all of chs.19-22) and rejected it.</p>',
'68': '<p>"And if I asked you, you would not answer" -- Jesus turns the interrogation: I could ask you questions (presumably about his authority, his identity as Son of David, his relation to John\'s baptism -- all of which he has already posed in 20:1-8, 41-44) and you would not engage. The exchange that follows is not a courtroom testimony but a declaration: Jesus refuses to be positioned as a defendant pleading for acquittal before a court he does not recognize as having legitimate authority over him. His two conditions (you won\'t believe; you won\'t answer) reveal that the "trial" is not a legal proceeding but a confrontation between two incompatible claims to authority.</p>',
'69': '<p>"But from now on (apo tou nyn), the Son of Man will be seated at the right hand of the mighty God" -- the direct reference to Ps 110:1 ("The LORD says to my lord: Sit at my right hand until I make your enemies a footstool for your feet") combined with Dan 7:13 ("one like a son of man, coming with the clouds of heaven") in a single declaration. "From now on" is uniquely Lukan: not "you will see" (as in Mark 14:62 and Matt 26:64) but "from now on" -- the exaltation begins with the passion, not despite it. The seated position (kath&#275;menos) is the posture of authority and judgment (not servitude). "The right hand of the mighty God" (d&#275;namin tou theou = the power/might of God) is the position of supreme authority in the cosmos.</p>',
'70': '<p>"They all asked: Are you then the Son of God? He replied: You say that I am (hymeis legete hoti ego eimi = you say that I am)" -- the Son of God question follows naturally from the Son of Man / right hand of God declaration: if Jesus claims to sit at God\'s right hand, the implication is divine sonship. The phrase "You say that I am" is a qualified affirmation -- not exactly "yes" but not a denial: you have stated it correctly. The formula echoes the earlier "You say so" to Pilate (23:3). The council interprets it as affirmation (v.71: "we have heard it from his own lips") -- the statement is sufficient for their purposes regardless of its precise epistemic status.</p>',
'71': '<p>"Why do we need any more testimony? We have heard it from his own lips" (autoi gar ēkousamen apo tou stomatos autou = for we ourselves have heard it from his own mouth) -- the Sanhedrin concludes that Jesus\'s statement constitutes self-incriminating testimony. In Jewish legal procedure (m. Sanhedrin 9:5-6), one\'s own admission was the highest form of evidence. The council does not issue a formal verdict at this point in Luke (unlike Mark 14:64: "condemned as worthy of death"): Luke\'s Sanhedrin hearing functions more as an examination that produces a charge to take to Pilate. Their concluding statement that they have "heard it from his own lips" frames the hearing as complete: the charge of blasphemy or false messianic claim now has Jesus\'s own words as its basis for the Roman referral.</p>',
}
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'luke')
    merge_comm(existing, NEW)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'luke', existing)
    import json as _j, pathlib as _pl
    inter = _j.loads((_pl.Path(__file__).parent.parent / 'data/interlinear/luke.json').read_text())
    for ch in [22]:
        ck = str(ch)
        have = set(existing.get(ck, {}).keys())
        need = set(inter.get(ck, {}).keys())
        missing = sorted(int(v) for v in (need - have))
        print(f'  ch{ch}: {len(have)}/{len(need)} -- missing: {missing}')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
